   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": "## Splitting into Train and Eval Sets\n\nWe hold out 10% of examples as a validation set. Evaluating on a held-out set during training lets us detect overfitting: if training loss decreases while validation loss starts increasing, the model is memorising rather than generalising."
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "kWJC_gamSZEG"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": "# \u2500\u2500 Train / eval split \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\n# In DEMO mode use only 1,000 examples to keep training under a few minutes.\n# In full mode use the entire dataset.\nif DEMO:\n    k = 200\nelse:\n    k = len(data)\n\neval_proportion = 0.1         # hold out 10 % of examples for validation\neval_size  = int(k * eval_proportion)\ntrain_size = k - eval_size\n\n# Shuffle with a fixed seed so the split is the same every run\nshuffled_data = data.shuffle(seed=params.seed)\nsampled_data  = shuffled_data.select(range(k))\n\n# Slice off the first train_size rows for training, the rest for evaluation\ntrain_data = sampled_data.select(range(train_size))\neval_data  = sampled_data.select(range(train_size, k))"
  },
